# =============================================================================
# Q44: The Procession of Creatures from God, and of the First Cause of All
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "44.0", "refashioned": "Having examined the procession of the divine persons, we now turn to how creatures proceed from God. This divides into three topics: the production of creatures, their distinction from one another, and their preservation and governance. On production, we ask about the first cause of beings, how creatures emanate from that cause, and whether creation has a temporal beginning. Four questions open this inquiry: Is God the efficient cause of all beings? Is primary matter created by God or independent of him? Is God the exemplar cause? And is God the final cause of all things?"})

data.append({"index": "44.1", "refashioned": "Everything that exists in any way whatsoever is from God. Here is why. Whatever a thing has by participation must be caused by whatever has that trait essentially. Iron becomes hot through fire, which is heat by nature. God is self-subsistent being itself. There can only be one such being, just as there could only be one self-subsisting whiteness. Everything else, then, does not possess existence on its own but participates in it. And whatever participates in being must ultimately be caused by the one who possesses being most perfectly.\n\nPlato made the same point: unity must precede multiplicity. Aristotle agreed: whatever is greatest in being and truth is the cause of all being and truth.\n\nOne might object that the relation of effect to cause is not part of a thing's definition, so things could exist uncaused. But the relation follows necessarily from what a thing is. Because a thing has being only by participation, it must be caused. An uncaused being is possible in principle, but only if that being exists through itself rather than by participation.\n\nAnother objection: necessary things cannot fail to exist, so they need no cause. But this confuses two issues. A cause is needed not merely because an effect might not exist, but because the effect depends on the cause for its existence. Even necessary truths in mathematics have causes, as Aristotle recognized.\n\nAs for mathematics not using efficient causes in its demonstrations: mathematics abstracts from matter and studies formal relations. That its proofs do not reference efficient causes does not mean its objects lack them. It simply means efficient causation is not the lens through which mathematics examines reality."})

data.append({"index": "44.2", "refashioned": "Primary matter itself is created by God. Earlier thinkers only considered how particular things emerge from particular causes and so assumed matter was a given starting point. But the question here is not about particular transformations. It is about the origin of being as such. Everything that exists in any way participates in being. Matter, as pure potentiality, has a real share in existence. Therefore it too must derive from the universal cause of all being.\n\nThe objection that matter has no prior subject from which to be made misses the point. Creation is not a change from one state to another. It is the bringing forth of being where there was nothing at all. The objection that God and matter are two co-equal principles, one active and one passive, also fails. Matter is not on the same level as God. Even matter's potentiality is a participation in being, and so it depends on God as its source."})

data.append({"index": "44.3", "refashioned": "God is the exemplar cause of all things, and no other exemplar cause is needed. An exemplar cause is the pattern or model according to which something is made. Since God produces things through his intellect rather than by natural necessity, and since his intellect contains the ideas of all things, his essence serves as the model for everything created.\n\nPlato was right that forms or patterns are needed to explain why things are produced in determinate ways. But these patterns do not need to exist as independent entities outside the divine mind. God's essence, understood as imitable in various degrees by various creatures, contains all the exemplar ideas. Each creature is modeled on God's understanding of how his perfection can be participated in a particular way.\n\nThe objection that creatures are too unlike God to have him as their model confuses the issue. An exemplar does not require exact resemblance. It requires that the effect be produced according to the pattern. Creatures fall short of God, but they are still made in accordance with the ideas in his mind."})

data.append({"index": "44.4", "refashioned": "God is the final cause, the ultimate purpose, of all things. Every agent acts for an end. God, as the first agent, acts for an end too. His end can only be his own goodness, since he needs nothing outside himself. But this means that everything God creates is directed toward his goodness as its ultimate purpose.\n\nThis does not mean God acts out of need. A generous agent can act for an end without lacking anything. God creates not to acquire goodness but to communicate it. Every creature, by its very existence and activity, tends toward some likeness of divine goodness. That is its purpose.\n\nThe objection that purpose implies need confuses the agent's end with the agent's deficiency. The objection that the end, form, and agent cannot be identical conflates the end of the process with the end of the agent. God's goodness is both why he creates and what creation ultimately reflects."})

# =============================================================================
# Q45: The Mode of Emanation of Things from the First Cause
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "45.0", "refashioned": "We now consider how things emanate from God, which is called creation. Eight questions: What is creation? Can God create? Is creation something real in the creature? What kinds of things are created? Does creation belong to God alone? Is creation proper to any one divine person? Is there a trace of the Trinity in creatures? And is creation mixed into the works of nature and art?"})

data.append({"index": "45.1", "refashioned": "To create is to make something from nothing. Not \"nothing\" as a material cause, as if something were fashioned out of nothingness the way a statue is carved from marble. Rather, creation means producing being absolutely, without any pre-existing subject. In ordinary change, something becomes something else. In creation, there is no prior something at all.\n\nThis distinguishes creation from every other kind of production. Every natural process presupposes material to work with. Creation does not. It is the bringing forth of the whole substance of a thing into existence.\n\nThe objection that the noblest action should go from being to being rather than from nothing to something reverses the logic. Creation is nobler precisely because it requires no presupposed material. It produces being itself, which is more fundamental than any transformation of what already exists."})

data.append({"index": "45.2a", "refashioned": "God can create, meaning he can bring things into existence from nothing. The ancient axiom that \"nothing comes from nothing\" applied to particular agents working on pre-existing material. It does not apply to the universal cause of all being. A particular cause reshapes what already exists. The universal cause produces existence itself.\n\nThe further one traces the chain of causes back, the wider the scope of the effect and the less presupposed by the cause. A local artisan presupposes raw materials. A higher cause presupposes less. The highest cause presupposes nothing at all. That is what creation means.\n\nCreation is also not a \"change\" in the strict sense. Change requires a subject that persists through the transition. In creation there is no persisting subject, because the whole being comes into existence at once."})

data.append({"index": "45.2b", "refashioned": "The ancient philosophers said \"nothing comes from nothing\" because they only considered particular causes producing particular effects, which always presuppose existing material. That principle does not apply to the universal origin of all things.\n\nCreation is not change in the proper sense, since change requires a before and after in the same subject. But we can speak of creation as a kind of change in a loose sense: we can say the creature, after creation, exists in a way it did not before. This is a conceptual framework, not a claim about a temporal process.\n\nAs for the objection that creation requires infinite power because the distance between nothing and something is infinite: the \"distance\" between nonbeing and being is not a measurable gap. Creation does not cross a distance. It produces being where there was none."})

data.append({"index": "45.3", "refashioned": "Creation is something real in the creature, but it is not a change or a movement. It is the very dependence of the creature's being on God. Think of it this way: the creature's existence is a real relation of total dependence on its creator. This relation is not something added on top of the creature's existence. It is the creature's existence itself, understood as received from God.\n\nThe objection that creation cannot be in the creature because it would then be something temporal in God confuses active and passive creation. Actively, creation is God's eternal act. Passively, creation is the creature's real relation of dependence, which begins with the creature. The objection that creation must be a medium between Creator and creature is misleading. Creation is not a bridge between two pre-existing things. It is the very act by which the creature comes to be."})

data.append({"index": "45.4", "refashioned": "Creation properly belongs to composite, subsisting things, not to abstract parts or forms considered in isolation. What is created is the whole being, the complete substance. We do not say that matter alone is created, or form alone, but that the entire composite thing is brought into existence.\n\nThis holds even for simple spiritual substances. Although they lack matter, they are still complete subsisting beings, and their whole being is produced by creation. The key criterion is that creation produces subsisting entities, things that exist in themselves rather than merely as aspects of something else."})

data.append({"index": "45.5a", "refashioned": "Creation belongs to God alone. No creature can create, because creation means producing being from nothing, which requires infinite power. Here is why: the greater the distance between a cause's starting point and its effect, the more power is required. Since in creation there is no starting point at all, no pre-existing material, the power required is beyond anything finite.\n\nA creature can produce a likeness of itself through natural generation or through art, but it always works with pre-existing material. It reshapes what already exists. Only God, whose power is infinite and who is existence itself, can bring something into being from nothing.\n\nThe idea that God could delegate creative power to a creature, using it as an instrument, also fails. An instrument contributes something of its own to the effect. But in creation, there is no pre-existing material for an instrument to work on. An instrument that contributes nothing is not really an instrument."})

data.append({"index": "45.5b", "refashioned": "When a creature produces something like itself, it does not produce the nature absolutely. It applies an existing nature to new material. A man does not create human nature. He transmits it to a new individual through generation, presupposing determinate matter. Similarly, every created being participates in existence rather than possessing it essentially. Only God, who is his own existence, can produce existence itself. Every other agent merely communicates a participated likeness within material that already exists."})

data.append({"index": "45.6a", "refashioned": "Creation is not the exclusive act of any one divine person, but is common to the whole Trinity. Since the divine persons share one essence and one power, they share one creative act. However, the way we attribute creation can reflect the distinct personal properties: to the Father as origin, to the Son as exemplar (through whom all things are made), and to the Holy Spirit as governing love that directs creatures toward their good.\n\nThe processions of the divine persons are the cause of creation. The Son proceeds as the Word, containing the intellectual pattern of all creatures. The Spirit proceeds as Love, containing the impulse that gives creatures their relation to their end. But causation belongs to the divine essence, not to the relations alone, so creation is common to all three."})

data.append({"index": "45.6b", "refashioned": "The divine nature, though common to all three persons, belongs to them in a certain order: the Son receives it from the Father, the Spirit from both. The same holds for creative power. The Father creates as one who has creative power from no one else. The Son creates as one who receives that power from the Father along with the divine nature. The Spirit creates as receiving from both. This is why Scripture attributes creation to the Father as source, through the Son as pattern, and in the Spirit as sustaining love. But the act itself is one and undivided."})

data.append({"index": "45.7", "refashioned": "Every creature bears a trace of the Trinity. A trace is not a full image, the way the rational mind images the Trinity, but a mark left by the cause in its effect. Every creature has three features that point back to the Trinity: it has a determinate existence (pointing to the Father as origin), a determinate form or species (pointing to the Son as the Word and exemplar), and a determinate relation to other things and to its own good (pointing to the Holy Spirit as love).\n\nThis is not a proof of the Trinity from creation. The Trinity can only be known through revelation. But once the Trinity is known, we can recognize its vestiges in the structure of every created thing. The threefold character of creatures, their being, their form, and their order, reflects, however faintly, the threefold character of their source."})

data.append({"index": "45.8", "refashioned": "Creation is not mixed into the ordinary works of nature or art. When nature produces a new form in existing matter, the form is not created from nothing. It is educed from the potentiality of the matter by the action of a natural agent. The substantial form does not come into being on its own. It comes into being as part of the composite, and the composite comes into being through natural transformation, not creation.\n\nThe same applies to art. An artist does not create the form of the artwork from nothing. The artist imposes form on pre-existing material through skill and effort. In every case, natural and artificial production presuppose existing matter and work by transforming it. Creation, by contrast, produces the whole substance. The two are fundamentally different kinds of causation."})

# =============================================================================
# Q46: Of the Beginning of the Duration of Creatures
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "46.0", "refashioned": "We now consider whether the created world had a beginning. Three questions: Did the universe always exist? Is its temporal beginning an article of faith? And what does it mean that God created heaven and earth \"in the beginning\"?"})

data.append({"index": "46.1a", "refashioned": "The universe has not always existed. Only God can be eternal. God's will is the cause of all things, and God is not compelled to will that the world exist from eternity. He freely wills the world into existence at whatever duration he chooses.\n\nSeveral arguments for an eternal world fail. The claim that what can exist must have always been possible, and that possibility requires pre-existing matter, confuses active and passive potentiality. Before the world existed, it was possible by God's active power, not by some pre-existing matter. The claim that anything with the power to exist forever must have always existed conflates having that power forever with having existed forever. A thing receives its power to endure when it is created, not before."})

data.append({"index": "46.1b", "refashioned": "Nothing except God can be eternal. God's will is the cause of things, and it is not necessary for God to will that the world always exist. The world exists for as long as God wills it. Since God freely chose a finite duration for the world, the world has a beginning. Its existence is entirely contingent on the divine will, which is under no necessity to produce an everlasting cosmos."})

data.append({"index": "46.1c", "refashioned": "Before the world existed, its possibility rested on God's active power, not on any pre-existing material. The objection that things capable of perpetual existence must have always existed fails: a thing receives its capacity for endurance at the moment of its creation. It does not follow that it lacked a beginning.\n\nThe argument that God's active power is eternal, and therefore its effect should be eternal, also fails. An agent that acts by will, not by natural necessity, can produce an effect whenever it chooses. A voluntary agent is not compelled to produce its effect the instant it has the power to do so. God freely determined both that the world should exist and when it should begin.\n\nAs for the objection that God's action must be eternal because God is eternal: God's action is identical with his being, which is indeed eternal. But the effect of that action begins when God wills it to begin. The eternal act produces a temporal result by free choice."})

data.append({"index": "46.2a", "refashioned": "That the world had a beginning is an article of faith, not a conclusion that can be demonstrated by reason alone. We can prove that God is the efficient cause of the world. But we cannot prove by reason that God did not will the world to exist from eternity. The world's temporal beginning depends on God's free choice, and free choices cannot be deduced from necessary principles.\n\nThe arguments claiming to demonstrate a temporal beginning all have flaws. Some argue that an infinite series of past events is impossible. But this confuses different kinds of infinity. An infinite past series is not simultaneously existing; each moment passes away. Others argue that an actually infinite number of souls would exist if the world were eternal, but this depends on contested premises about the soul's relation to time.\n\nThe world's beginning is known by faith, through revelation. Reason can show it is not impossible for the world to have begun, but reason cannot prove it did."})

data.append({"index": "46.2b", "refashioned": "Some philosophers held that the world is eternal but still created by God. They meant that the world has a beginning of creation but not a beginning of time, that God always sustained it in existence. Augustine compared this to a foot eternally planted in dust: the footprint would be eternal too, yet still caused by the foot. This view is logically coherent but incorrect according to faith.\n\nThe arguments purporting to demonstrate a beginning of time are not airtight. They show that a beginning is possible, even fitting, but not that it is necessary. The strongest ground for affirming a temporal beginning remains revelation, not philosophical demonstration. Those who attempted rational proofs actually weakened the case for faith by offering arguments that opponents could easily rebut."})

data.append({"index": "46.3", "refashioned": "Creation was in the beginning of time. Time itself began with creation. There was no pre-existing time into which the world was placed. Rather, the first moment of the world's existence was the first moment of time.\n\nThe objection that creation is not in time because substance as such is not measured by time misses the point. While the substance of things is not directly temporal, the beginning of existence is. The phrase \"in the beginning\" refers to the first instant in which things came to be, the point at which time itself commenced."})

# =============================================================================
# Q47: Of the Distinction of Things in General
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "47.0", "refashioned": "Having considered the production of creatures, we turn to their distinction. Why are things different from one another? Three questions: Does the multitude and variety of things come from God? Does the inequality of things come from God? And is there only one world?"})

data.append({"index": "47.1a", "refashioned": "The multitude and distinction of things comes from God's intention, not from chance, natural necessity, or any secondary cause. God is a voluntary agent who acts through intellect. Unlike a natural agent that can only produce one kind of effect, an intellectual agent can intend many different effects. God created diverse things because no single creature can adequately represent his goodness. The whole universe, with its variety, expresses what no individual creature could.\n\nThe Manichean view that distinction arises from opposing good and evil principles fails because distinction is not a defect. It is a perfection of the whole. Other views, that diversity comes from secondary causes or matter, also fail. They reduce the origin of the world's richness to accident rather than design. The variety of creation is not a byproduct. It is the point."})

data.append({"index": "47.1b", "refashioned": "A natural agent, acting by a single form, produces only one kind of effect. But a voluntary agent acting through intellect can produce many different effects. Since God is a voluntary agent, his unity does not prevent him from making diverse things.\n\nNor does the fact that God is the exemplar of creation require that creation be uniform. A single exemplar can be imitated in multiple ways, at varying degrees of likeness. The diversity of creatures represents the many ways God's goodness can be participated."})

data.append({"index": "47.2a", "refashioned": "The inequality of things is from God, by intention. A universe of unequal beings is better than one in which everything is equal, because unequal parts form a more complete whole. An organism made entirely of eyes would be no organism at all. Similarly, the universe achieves its perfection through a hierarchy of beings, from the simplest to the most complex, each contributing something the others cannot.\n\nThe objection that the best agent should produce the best possible individual things confuses part with whole. God produces the best possible whole. That requires different grades of perfection. The inequality of creatures is not a defect in God's goodness but its fullest expression.\n\nThe further objection that inequality must come from merit or demerit rather than from God directly gets the order backward. Inequality of nature precedes any inequality of action. Things must first be different before they can act differently."})

data.append({"index": "47.2b", "refashioned": "The best agent produces the best total effect, not the best individual part. In an organism, removing inequality would destroy the whole. Each part has its goodness in proportion to the whole. God made the universe as a graded hierarchy because that is what perfection in a created whole requires. Each creature is good, but the ordered totality is better than any collection of equals."})

data.append({"index": "47.3", "refashioned": "There is only one world. Since God created all things for his goodness, and the order among things is itself part of what expresses that goodness, the unity of the world's order requires that there be one cosmos. If there were multiple worlds, either they would be unrelated (which would introduce purposeless diversity) or they would form a single ordered whole (making them one world after all).\n\nThe objection that God's infinite power means he could and should create many worlds fails. God's power is not measured by the number of worlds but by the perfection of what he produces. One well-ordered world better reflects divine wisdom than multiple uncoordinated ones."})

# =============================================================================
# Q48: The Distinction of Things in Particular (Good and Evil)
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "48.0", "refashioned": "We turn now to the distinction of good and evil. Six questions about evil: Is evil a nature? Does evil exist in things? Is good the subject of evil? Does evil destroy good entirely? Is evil rightly divided into suffering and fault? And which has more the character of evil, suffering or fault?"})

data.append({"index": "48.1a", "refashioned": "Evil is not a nature or a positive reality. It is the absence of good. Everything that exists, insofar as it exists, is good. Every nature desires its own being and perfection, and whatever is desirable is good. So being and goodness are convertible. Evil, therefore, cannot signify any being or form. It signifies only the absence of a good that should be present.\n\nThis does not mean evil is merely nothing. A privation is not just any absence but the absence of something that ought to be there. Blindness is not simply the lack of wings; it is the lack of sight in a being that should have sight. Evil is real in this sense: it is a genuine privation, a real gap in what should be whole."})

data.append({"index": "48.1b", "refashioned": "Aristotle's classification of good and evil as genera reflected the Pythagorean view, not his own settled position. In reality, evil is not a genus but a privation. When evil appears to constitute a species of morality, as when we say a habit is \"bad,\" the species is defined not by a positive nature but by a privation of due order. Good and evil are not contraries in the strict sense of two positive natures opposing each other. Evil is opposed to good as privation to possession.\n\nAs for the objection that evil acts and therefore must be real: evil does not act on its own power. It acts through the good that remains in the defective subject. A disease destroys health not by its own positive power but through the disordered action of the body's remaining capacities."})

data.append({"index": "48.2", "refashioned": "Evil does exist in things, not as a positive being but as a real privation. Wherever there is a creature capable of falling short of its proper perfection, evil can occur. And since every creature is finite, every creature can fall short in some respect.\n\nEvil is found in things because the perfection of the universe requires corruptible beings alongside incorruptible ones. The interaction of diverse natural agents inevitably produces some corruption. Fire warms but also burns. The good of the whole requires these interactions, even though they sometimes result in the privation of good in particular things.\n\nThe objection that evil cannot exist because it is neither being nor non-being misses the point. Evil is a real privation within a being. It is not a substance, but it is genuinely present in substances as a deficiency."})

data.append({"index": "48.3", "refashioned": "Evil can only exist in good as its subject. This sounds paradoxical but follows necessarily. Evil is a privation, the absence of a good that should be present. A privation can only exist in something that has, or should have, the missing perfection. Blindness can only exist in a being that ought to see. Therefore every subject of evil must itself be something good, since every existing thing is good insofar as it exists.\n\nThis means pure evil is impossible. Evil always parasitizes some good. A thoroughly evil thing, one with no goodness whatsoever, could not exist at all, because to exist is itself a good. The worse something becomes, the less it exists in the full sense. But as long as it exists at all, some good remains."})

data.append({"index": "48.4a", "refashioned": "Evil cannot completely destroy good. It can eliminate the particular good to which it is opposed: disease can destroy health. But it cannot destroy the underlying subject or its capacity for good entirely. As long as the subject exists, it retains some good, namely its existence and its fundamental capacity for perfection.\n\nThink of it this way: evil diminishes the aptitude for good, the subject's readiness to achieve its proper perfection. But this aptitude can be diminished endlessly without ever being fully extinguished, because it is rooted in the subject's very nature. The subject's existence is the good that cannot be destroyed without destroying the subject altogether, at which point evil itself would have no foothold."})

data.append({"index": "48.4b", "refashioned": "The particular good opposed to a given evil can be wholly removed. Disease wholly removes health. But the underlying goods, the subject's existence and its basic capacity for restoration, remain. Good is not uniform; it has layers. Evil can strip away one layer while leaving others intact. This is why evil can always diminish good further but never finish the job completely."})

data.append({"index": "48.5", "refashioned": "Evil is rightly divided into two kinds: suffering (or penalty) and fault (or sin). Evil is the privation of good. But \"good\" means different things in different contexts. The good of an agent's proper action is one thing; the good of the agent's own being is another. Fault is the privation of right action: the agent fails to act as it should. Suffering is the privation of something in the agent's own being or condition: something the agent has or should have is taken away.\n\nThese two are connected. Suffering follows from fault as its natural consequence, because a failure of right order in action produces a corresponding disorder in the agent's condition. But not all suffering traces to the individual's own fault. Sometimes it flows from the order of the whole, in which one part suffers for the correction or good of another."})

data.append({"index": "48.6", "refashioned": "Fault has more the character of evil than suffering does. Suffering is the privation of some good in the agent's being or condition. Fault is the privation of right order in the agent's action. But right action is a greater good than mere well-being, because action is the purpose for which capacities exist. A power exists for the sake of its proper act, not the reverse.\n\nMoreover, suffering can be involuntary and does not always diminish the agent's moral worth. Fault is voluntary and directly corrupts the will's relation to the good. Suffering is the consequence of disorder; fault is the disorder itself. The disease is worse than the symptom.\n\nThe objection that suffering opposes the agent's good while fault only opposes the good of action, and the agent is higher than the action, reverses the real priority. The agent's highest good is right action. Suffering harms what the agent has. Fault harms what the agent is for."})

# =============================================================================
# Q49: The Cause of Evil
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "49.0", "refashioned": "We now ask about the cause of evil. Three questions: Can good cause evil? Is God the cause of evil? And is there a supreme evil that is the first cause of all evils?"})

data.append({"index": "49.1a", "refashioned": "Good is the cause of evil, but only incidentally. Evil has no cause of its own, because evil is not a positive thing but a privation. A privation does not have an efficient cause in the way a positive reality does. What causes evil is a good agent that falls short, either in its power or in its action.\n\nIn nature, evil results from the collision of goods. Fire is good, but it destroys wood. The good of one thing causes the privation of another. In voluntary action, evil results from a defective will, which is itself a created good that fails to maintain right order. The will does not aim at evil as evil. It aims at some apparent good while failing to attend to the order it should maintain.\n\nSo evil always traces back to a good cause acting deficiently. Evil is a byproduct of finite goods interacting, not a force with its own independent origin."})

data.append({"index": "49.1b", "refashioned": "A good will does not produce morally evil acts. But the will as a natural power, which is itself good, can produce a disordered act. Good causes evil not by intending evil but by falling short in execution or in the ordering of its action. Fire does not intend to destroy; it intends to burn, and destruction is a side effect. The human will does not choose evil as evil; it chooses a lesser good while neglecting the proper order of goods."})

data.append({"index": "49.2", "refashioned": "God is not the cause of moral evil. He is, however, the cause of the natural order in which suffering and physical evil occur. When Scripture says God \"creates evil,\" it refers to the natural evils of punishment, disaster, and correction, not to sin.\n\nGod is the cause of every being and every action insofar as it has being. But the deficiency in an action, the part that constitutes its evil, comes from the defective secondary cause, not from God. An analogy: the power of locomotion causes walking, but the limp comes from the crooked leg, not from the motive power itself. God gives every agent its power to act. When that agent acts deficiently, the deficiency is the agent's own, not God's.\n\nGod permits evil because the perfection of the universe requires the possibility of failure in finite agents. But permitting evil and causing evil are fundamentally different."})

data.append({"index": "49.3a", "refashioned": "Is there a supreme evil that causes all other evils, as God is the supreme good that causes all goods? Several arguments suggest so: contraries should have contrary causes; if supreme good exists in nature, so should supreme evil; evil seems to grow endlessly, suggesting an infinite source."})

data.append({"index": "49.3b", "refashioned": "There is no supreme evil, no first principle of evil standing opposite to God. This follows from everything established so far.\n\nFirst, the supreme good is essentially good. But nothing can be essentially evil, because every being, insofar as it exists, is good. A being that was pure evil would have no existence at all.\n\nSecond, the supreme good contains all goodness perfectly. But a supreme evil containing all evil is impossible, because total evil would destroy itself. Evil can only exist by parasitizing good. The more evil something becomes, the less it exists. Complete evil is complete non-existence.\n\nThird, evil is always accidental and particular, never essential and universal. It arises from the deficiency of particular causes, not from some cosmic anti-principle. Evil has no unified source because it is not a unified phenomenon. It is the many different ways finite things can fall short."})

data.append({"index": "49.3c", "refashioned": "Contraries within nature do share a common genus and a common cause, but evil is not the true contrary of good. It is a privation. Privation and possession naturally belong to the same subject, but the supreme good has no potentiality and therefore cannot be the subject of any privation. Evil opposes the kind of good that can fail, not the good that is pure act.\n\nAs for evil appearing to grow endlessly: evil diminishes good but cannot eliminate it entirely, as established earlier. This endless diminution does not point to an infinite source of evil. It points to the fact that finite good, while inexhaustible at its root, can always be further diminished by deficient causes."})

# =============================================================================
# Q50: Of the Substance of the Angels Absolutely Considered
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "50.0", "refashioned": "We now turn from the general production of creatures to the distinction between spiritual and corporeal beings. We begin with purely spiritual creatures, called angels in Scripture. We consider first their substance (both absolutely and in relation to bodies), then their knowledge, then their will, and finally their creation. On angelic substance considered absolutely, five questions: Are angels entirely incorporeal? Are they composed of matter and form? How many are there? Do they differ in species? And are they incorruptible?"})

data.append({"index": "50.1", "refashioned": "Angels are entirely incorporeal. The perfection of the universe requires intellectual creatures, beings that know and understand. But intelligence cannot be the function of a body. Every body is confined to a particular place and time, while understanding grasps universal truths that transcend spatial and temporal limits. So the universe must contain beings that are incorporeal.\n\nEarlier thinkers who denied incorporeal beings made the mistake of assuming that only what can be sensed or imagined is real. They collapsed intellect into sensation. But the very fact that our intellect rises above sense perception, grasping abstract truths that no sense organ could register, is proof that there must be incorporeal realities.\n\nThe objection that angels are called corporeal compared to God does not mean they have bodies. It means they are limited, unlike God who is unlimited. Every creature has boundaries, but spiritual creatures are bounded by their essence, not by physical dimensions."})

data.append({"index": "50.2a", "refashioned": "Angels are not composed of matter and form. In material beings, matter is what gives individuality within a species, while form gives the species itself. But angels are not individuated by matter. Each angel is a pure form, subsisting on its own.\n\nThis does not mean angels have no potentiality at all. They are not pure act, which belongs to God alone. But their composition is not of matter and form. It is of essence and existence. An angel's essence (what it is) is distinct from its existence (that it is). This is the fundamental composition in every creature: only God is his own existence.\n\nThe objection that angels must have matter because they are in a genus (substance) confuses material and logical composition. Genus and species in immaterial beings come not from matter and form but from the degree of perfection of the form itself. Different grades of immaterial perfection generate different species without any matter."})

data.append({"index": "50.2b", "refashioned": "In material things, genus derives from matter and specific difference from form. In immaterial things, this does not apply. Instead, different grades of perfection within the form itself account for both genus and difference. Each species of angel is constituted by a form at a specific degree of perfection. The more perfect the form, the more universal its power of understanding.\n\nThe objection that angels must have matter because they receive existence from God also fails. Receiving existence makes an angel composed of essence and existence, but this is not a matter-form composition. Matter is pure potentiality for physical form. An angel's essence is an actual intelligible nature, not potentiality for physical configuration."})

data.append({"index": "50.3a", "refashioned": "Angels exist in vast numbers, far exceeding the number of material things. Since immaterial beings are more perfect than material ones, the perfection of the universe demands that they be the most abundant class of beings. Material species are multiplied within each species by matter: there are many individual humans, dogs, or stars. But angelic species are multiplied without matter, meaning there are many distinct species of angel, each a unique grade of intellectual perfection.\n\nScripture confirms this abundance: \"Thousands of thousands ministered to him, and ten thousand times ten thousand stood before him.\" The point is not a literal count but that the angelic host surpasses all material multiplicity."})

data.append({"index": "50.3b", "refashioned": "Angelic number is not the kind of quantity that comes from dividing a continuous body. It is the multiplicity that comes from distinct forms. Since each angel is its own species, the number of angels is the number of distinct grades of intellectual being. Their closeness to God's unity does not mean they are few. Rather, the simplicity of their composition allows for a greater diversity of species than material things can achieve."})

data.append({"index": "50.4", "refashioned": "Each angel differs in species from every other angel. In material beings, matter allows multiple individuals to share one form: many humans share human nature because matter individuates them. Angels have no matter. So there cannot be two angels of the same species. Each angel is a unique species, a distinct grade of intellectual being.\n\nThe objection that angels differ only by degree (more or less perfect) and that degree does not change species fails. In immaterial beings, every different degree of perfection constitutes a different species. It is not like one human being smarter than another. It is like the difference between fundamentally different kinds of intellectual nature."})

data.append({"index": "50.5", "refashioned": "Angels are incorruptible. Corruption occurs when form separates from matter. Since angels have no matter, they cannot undergo this kind of dissolution. Their being is a pure subsisting form, and such a form cannot lose itself.\n\nEven if we consider that angels are composed of essence and existence (and so are not absolutely simple), this composition does not make them corruptible. Form separates from matter through natural processes. But existence does not separate from essence through any natural process. Only God, who gave existence, could annihilate it. And God does not annihilate what he has created, because his will sustains all things in being permanently.\n\nSo angels are naturally incorruptible, and they are preserved in existence by God's will, which does not withdraw what it has given."})

# =============================================================================
# Q51: Of the Angels in Comparison with Bodies
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "51.0", "refashioned": "We now compare angels to bodies. Three questions: Do angels have bodies naturally united to them? Can they assume bodies? And do they perform living functions in assumed bodies?"})

data.append({"index": "51.1", "refashioned": "Angels do not have bodies naturally united to them. An intellectual substance does not need a body for its proper operation, which is understanding. Bodies would hinder rather than help angelic intelligence, since understanding operates without material organs.\n\nSome early thinkers attributed subtle bodies, made of air or fire, to angels. But this was based on the inability to conceive of incorporeal substance rather than on sound reasoning. Once we grasp that intellect operates without matter, there is no reason to assign bodies to purely intellectual beings.\n\nThe fact that angels sometimes appear in bodily form in Scripture does not prove they have natural bodies. These appearances involve assumed bodies, taken temporarily for the purpose of communication with humans."})

data.append({"index": "51.2", "refashioned": "Angels can assume bodies, not by being naturally united to them, but by moving and shaping material elements to produce an appearance of a living body. The assumed body is not animated by the angel the way our bodies are animated by our souls. It is more like a puppet: the angel moves it from the outside, using its power to produce visible and audible effects.\n\nThe purpose of these assumed bodies is to make the angel's presence and message perceptible to human senses. Angels operate in the spiritual realm, but when they need to interact with embodied humans, they take on visible form. The body is a tool for communication, not a natural part of the angel's being."})

data.append({"index": "51.3a", "refashioned": "Angels do not truly perform biological functions in the bodies they assume. They do not actually eat, breathe, or reproduce. When Scripture describes angels eating or speaking, the actions are apparent rather than real in the biological sense. An angel can move an assumed body so that it appears to eat, using air to form sounds that appear to be speech, but no genuine nutrition or respiration occurs.\n\nThis is not deception. Just as figurative language in Scripture is not false because no one takes it literally, so the appearance of life in an assumed body is not a lie. It is a visible sign of spiritual realities. The body serves as a medium for the angel's message, not as evidence that angels have biological life."})

data.append({"index": "51.3b", "refashioned": "The fact that angels in assumed bodies appear to perform living functions is similar to how Scripture uses sensible imagery to convey spiritual truths. Neither is deception. The assumed body is taken to represent spiritual properties through visible actions. Sensation in the assumed body is not real sensation. Speech is produced by manipulating air, not by biological vocal organs. If Scripture records angels eating, the food is dissolved by angelic power, not digested.\n\nThe essential point: assumed bodies are instruments of communication. Their apparent life is a sign, not a fact of angelic biology."})

# =============================================================================
# Q52: Of the Angels in Relation to Place
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "52.0", "refashioned": "Three questions about angels and place: Is an angel in a place? Can an angel be in several places at once? Can several angels be in the same place?"})

data.append({"index": "52.1", "refashioned": "An angel is in a place, but not in the way a body is. A body occupies place by filling it with its dimensions. An angel occupies place by applying its power to that location. Wherever an angel exercises its causal influence, that is where the angel is.\n\nSo angelic presence is defined by activity, not by spatial extension. An angel does not have dimensions that match a location's dimensions. Instead, the angel's power touches a place by acting there. This means angelic \"location\" is fundamentally different from bodily location, even though we use the same word."})

data.append({"index": "52.2", "refashioned": "An angel cannot be in multiple places simultaneously. Its power is finite, so when it applies itself to one location, it is definitively there and not elsewhere. The analogy with the soul, which is entirely in every part of the body, does not hold, because the soul is the form of the body and naturally present throughout it. An angel is not the form of any place.\n\nThe angel's presence in a place is determined by the scope of its application of power. It can be present to a large or small area depending on how broadly it acts, but it cannot be present in multiple unconnected places at the same time."})

data.append({"index": "52.3", "refashioned": "Two angels cannot be in the same place at the same time. Although angels do not fill space the way bodies do, each angel's presence in a place constitutes a complete application of spiritual power to that location. A second angel applying its power to the same location would imply that one place has two complete spiritual presences, which is as impossible in the spiritual order as two bodies occupying the same space is in the physical order.\n\nThe underlying principle is that a complete cause is sufficient for its effect. Two complete spiritual agents applied to the same place would mean one place with two sufficient spiritual presences, which is redundant and impossible."})

# =============================================================================
# Q53: Of the Local Movement of the Angels
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "53.0", "refashioned": "Three questions about angelic movement: Can an angel move from place to place? Must it pass through intermediate space? And is its movement instantaneous or in time?"})

data.append({"index": "53.1a", "refashioned": "An angel can move from place to place. Since an angel's presence in a place is defined by where it applies its power, it can successively apply its power to different places. This succession of presences constitutes local movement.\n\nAristotle's argument that nothing without parts can move locally applies to indivisible points within a continuous magnitude, not to immaterial beings. An angel is not a dimensionless point. It is a substance that can be wholly present to different places in succession. Its movement is not the physical displacement of a body but the successive application of spiritual power to different locations."})

data.append({"index": "53.1b", "refashioned": "Aristotle's proof that indivisible things cannot move applies to physical indivisibles, not to spiritual substances. An angel's movement can be either continuous, smoothly transitioning through space, or discontinuous, a succession of discrete presences. In the discontinuous case, the angel simply ceases to be in one place and begins to be in another, without physically traversing the interval.\n\nThe will is the principle of angelic movement. An angel moves because it wills to apply its power to a new location. This is fundamentally different from physical motion caused by external forces."})

data.append({"index": "53.2a", "refashioned": "Does an angel have to pass through every intermediate point when moving from one place to another? This depends on whether the movement is continuous or discontinuous."})

data.append({"index": "53.2b", "refashioned": "If an angel's movement is continuous, it must pass through intermediate space, just as any continuous motion traverses a path. But if the movement is discontinuous, the angel can go directly from one place to another without traversing the middle. It simply ceases to apply its power at the first location and begins to apply it at the second.\n\nThis discontinuous movement is possible because angelic presence is not tied to spatial extension. A body must traverse intermediate space because it physically occupies each point along the way. An angel's presence is a matter of applied power, and power can be applied to any location the angel's will selects, without needing to sweep through every intervening point."})

data.append({"index": "53.2c", "refashioned": "The angel's place is not sized to match it physically but to match its application of power. So angelic place can be divisible or indivisible depending on the scope of the angel's action. The soul's ability to think about distant things without traversing space is not a true parallel, because thought does not involve applying the soul's essence to a location. But the angel's movement does involve applying its essence. The key difference from bodily movement is that the application is voluntary and need not be spatially continuous."})

data.append({"index": "53.3a", "refashioned": "Is angelic movement instantaneous? If an angel can go from one place to another without passing through intermediate space, it might seem that movement is instantaneous. But the issue is more nuanced."})

data.append({"index": "53.3b", "refashioned": "Angelic movement is not instantaneous; it occurs in time, though not necessarily in the continuous time that measures physical motion. The time of angelic movement can be a succession of discrete instants rather than a smooth continuum.\n\nThe argument for instantaneous movement is that the angel's power infinitely exceeds any bodily resistance, so movement should take zero time. But this misunderstands what determines the speed of angelic movement. It is not a ratio of power to resistance but a matter of the angel's will determining how many successive positions to occupy and how quickly. The angel chooses the tempo of its movement.\n\nSome held that an angel is in the starting place for an entire preceding time and then in the destination at the last instant. But the more careful view is that angelic movement involves a real succession of positions in a real, though possibly non-continuous, time."})

data.append({"index": "53.3c", "refashioned": "If angelic time is not continuous but consists of a succession of discrete instants, it has no fixed ratio to continuous physical time. The swiftness of angelic movement is determined not by the magnitude of angelic power but by the angel's will. An angel can move faster or slower as it chooses, because its movement is volitional, not mechanical."})

# =============================================================================
# Q54: Of the Knowledge of the Angels
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "54.0", "refashioned": "We now turn from angelic substance to angelic knowledge. Four areas of inquiry: the power of angelic knowledge, its medium, its objects, and its mode. On the power of knowledge, five questions: Is understanding the angel's substance? Is understanding the same as existing for an angel? Is the angel's power of intelligence the same as its essence? Does the angel have both active and passive intellect? And is angelic knowledge purely intellectual?"})

data.append({"index": "54.1", "refashioned": "An angel's act of understanding is not identical with its substance. In God alone are being, essence, and activity one and the same. In every creature, including angels, there is a real distinction between what the thing is and what the thing does. The angel's substance is the foundation of its understanding, but understanding is an operation that proceeds from that substance.\n\nAristotle's claim that the intellect's action is its substance applies to the divine intellect, not to created intellects. A created intellect has potentiality: it can understand this or that. Its substance is actual in one way; its understanding is actual in another. The two are related as power to act."})

data.append({"index": "54.2", "refashioned": "In an angel, to understand is not the same as to exist. Existence is the angel's most fundamental actuality. Understanding is a further actuality that follows from it. The angel exists first, and then, by virtue of existing as an intellectual nature, it understands.\n\nIf understanding were identical with existence, then every degree of existence would be a degree of understanding, which is false. Many things exist without understanding. The angel's existence and its understanding are related but distinct acts. Existence is the ground; understanding is the operation that flows from it."})

data.append({"index": "54.3", "refashioned": "An angel's power of intelligence is distinct from its essence. Only in God is every attribute identical with the divine essence. In creatures, powers and capacities are really distinct from the substance they belong to. The angel's intellect is a power rooted in its essence but not identical with it.\n\nThis follows from the fact that the angel's act of understanding is distinct from its existence. If the power of understanding were identical with the essence, and the essence were identical with existence, then understanding would be identical with existing, which we just denied. So the power of understanding is something in the angel that flows from its essence as a capacity, ready to be actualized in particular acts of knowledge."})

data.append({"index": "54.4", "refashioned": "Angels do not have an active and passive intellect in the way humans do. Humans need an active intellect to abstract intelligible forms from sensory data and a passive intellect to receive those forms. Angels do not abstract from sensory data. They have intelligible forms directly, implanted by God at their creation.\n\nHowever, in a broad sense, there is something analogous to passive intellect in angels, since they receive intelligible forms rather than being those forms. They are not pure act in the order of knowledge. They have a capacity that is fulfilled by the forms they possess. But they lack an active intellect in the strict sense because they do not need to extract intelligibility from material things."})

data.append({"index": "54.5", "refashioned": "Angels have only intellectual knowledge, not sensation. They lack bodies and therefore lack sense organs. Since sensation requires a bodily organ, angels cannot sense. Memory, imagination, and experience, as they function in us, are tied to our bodily nature and do not exist in angels in the same form.\n\nThis does not mean angels are less knowledgeable than we are. Their intellectual knowledge is far more powerful and comprehensive than ours. What we achieve slowly through sensation, abstraction, and reasoning, they grasp immediately and completely through their innate intellectual forms. They do not need the stepping-stones of sense experience because they begin where we hope to end."})

# =============================================================================
# Q55: Of the Medium of the Angelic Knowledge
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "55.0", "refashioned": "Three questions about how angels know: Do they know everything through their own substance? Do they understand through innate species or species drawn from things? And do higher angels know through more universal species than lower angels?"})

data.append({"index": "55.1", "refashioned": "Angels do not know all things through their own substance alone. An angel knows itself through its own essence, since it is directly present to itself as an intelligible form. But other things are not identical with the angel's essence, so knowing them requires something additional.\n\nThat additional element is intelligible species, intellectual forms implanted by God at the angel's creation, through which the angel knows realities other than itself. These species are likenesses of things, not derived from the things themselves but from God, who contains the ideas of all things. The angel's mind is furnished with these forms from the start, like a library fully stocked at the moment of its construction."})

data.append({"index": "55.2a", "refashioned": "Angels do not derive their knowledge from things. Human intellect abstracts forms from sensory experience. Angelic intellect does not. Angels know through innate species that God implanted in them at creation. These species are likenesses of things, but they come from above (from God, the cause of things), not from below (from the things themselves).\n\nThis follows from the angel's nature as a purely intellectual being without senses. Since angels have no sensory apparatus, they cannot receive impressions from material things. Their knowledge of the material world comes through the innate forms God gave them, forms that represent material things as they exist in the divine creative plan."})

data.append({"index": "55.2b", "refashioned": "The images of creatures in the angel's mind are not derived from creatures but from God, in whom the ideas of all creatures originally exist. As Augustine puts it, the pattern of a creature exists in God's Word before the creature is made, and the knowledge of that pattern exists in the angelic mind before the creature comes into being.\n\nThis means angelic knowledge is a kind of participated divine knowledge. Angels know things as God designed them, through forms that reflect the creative plan rather than through forms extracted from created objects after the fact."})

data.append({"index": "55.3a", "refashioned": "Higher angels understand through more universal species than lower angels. A more powerful intellect can grasp more through a single concept. Where a lower angel might need many specific forms to know a range of things, a higher angel can know the same range through fewer, more comprehensive forms.\n\nThis is not a deficiency in the higher angel's knowledge. The higher angel's universal species are not vague generalizations. They contain everything the lower angel's particular species contain, and more. A single comprehensive form in a superior intellect captures all the detail that multiple narrower forms capture in an inferior one."})

data.append({"index": "55.3b", "refashioned": "The universality of angelic species is not the result of abstraction from particulars. It is a feature of how God furnishes different grades of intellect. A higher angel receives forms that are more universal by nature, not less detailed. The universal species of a higher angel is like a high-resolution map that covers a vast territory, compared to the lower angel's collection of detailed but narrower maps. Both capture the same reality, but the higher angel does so with greater unity and elegance."})

# =============================================================================
# Q56: Of the Angel's Knowledge of Immaterial Things
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "56.0", "refashioned": "Three questions about what angels know of immaterial realities: Does an angel know itself? Does one angel know another? And does an angel know God by natural means?"})

data.append({"index": "56.2a", "refashioned": "One angel can know another. Each angel possesses in its mind innate species representing other angels. Since an angel's nature is an intelligible form, and since other angelic natures are of the same general kind (immaterial intelligible forms differing in degree of perfection), each angel has a natural affinity with and knowledge of the others.\n\nThe objection that having a form of another nature within you would prevent knowing external things applies to material intellects corrupted by sensory data, not to immaterial intellects furnished with innate species. An angel's possession of another angel's species does not overwhelm its intellect any more than knowing one truth prevents you from knowing another."})

data.append({"index": "56.2b", "refashioned": "Angels know one another not because one causes the other, but because of the likeness among angelic natures. All angels share the general character of immaterial intellectual substance, differing only in degree of perfection. Each angel has innate species that represent other angelic natures. The species are not derived from the other angels but implanted by God, who created the whole order of angelic being."})

data.append({"index": "56.3", "refashioned": "An angel can know God through its natural powers, but only in a limited way. Since the angel's own nature is an effect of God, and effects bear some likeness to their cause, the angel can know God as its cause and origin. This natural knowledge of God is far superior to our natural knowledge, because the angel is a much closer likeness to God than any material creature.\n\nBut this natural knowledge falls infinitely short of knowing God as he is in himself. God's essence infinitely surpasses every created intellect. No angel can naturally comprehend God. To see God as he truly is requires supernatural elevation, the light of glory, which exceeds any creature's natural capacity. Natural angelic knowledge of God is real and profound, but it is still knowledge of God through a created likeness, not face-to-face vision."})

# =============================================================================
# Q57: Of the Angel's Knowledge of Material Things
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "57.0", "refashioned": "Five questions about angelic knowledge of the material world: Do angels know material things? Do they know individual particulars? Do they know the future? Do they know secret thoughts? And do they know the mysteries of grace?"})

data.append({"index": "57.1", "refashioned": "Angels know material things. Their innate species, received from God, represent not only immaterial realities but also the material world. Since God is the cause of both spiritual and material things, and since he furnished angels with knowledge through species that reflect his creative plan, those species encompass material creation as well.\n\nThe objection that material things are beneath angels and therefore cannot perfect them confuses the direction of knowledge. The angel is not perfected by the material thing itself but by the intelligible species that represents it. And that species comes from God, not from the material thing. Angels know the material world from above, through the divine ideas, not from below through sensory contact."})

data.append({"index": "57.2a", "refashioned": "Do angels know individual particular things, or only universals? This question matters because if angels cannot know singulars, they cannot govern the world, since all events involve individuals."})

data.append({"index": "57.2b", "refashioned": "Angels know individual things, not just universals. Denying this would undermine both faith and philosophy. Faith holds that angels administer particular affairs in the world, which requires knowledge of particulars. Philosophy holds that angels move the heavenly bodies and direct natural processes, which also requires knowledge of singulars.\n\nAngels know singulars because their innate species, coming from God, represent things as God knows them, and God knows all things in their individuality. Human intellect knows only universals directly because it abstracts from material conditions. But angelic species are not abstracted from matter. They are comprehensive representations that include both the universal nature and its individual instances."})

data.append({"index": "57.2c", "refashioned": "Aristotle's claim that intellect knows only universals while sense knows particulars applies to the human intellect, which works by abstraction from material conditions. Angelic intellect does not abstract from matter. Its species represent things completely, including their individuality. The higher bears a relation to the lower that includes the lower's details, not just its general features. So angelic knowledge of singulars does not reduce the angel to the level of sensation; it operates at a higher level that encompasses what sensation provides and more."})

data.append({"index": "57.3", "refashioned": "Angels do not know future contingent events as they are in themselves. The future, as contingent, does not yet exist in a determinate state. Only God, who sees all of time in a single eternal present, knows the future with certainty.\n\nHowever, angels can know some future events through their causes. When a cause necessarily produces a certain effect, the angel can predict it with certainty by knowing the cause. When a cause usually but not always produces an effect, the angel can predict it with probability, the way an experienced physician predicts the likely course of a disease. But events that depend on free will or on the convergence of independent causal chains remain unknowable to angels in advance.\n\nProphetic knowledge of the future is a different matter. That comes from divine revelation, not from angelic natural knowledge."})

data.append({"index": "57.4a", "refashioned": "Angels cannot know the secret thoughts and free choices of other minds. Thoughts exist in the will and intellect, and their expression depends on the will's free decision to manifest or conceal them. Only God, who is the direct cause and sustainer of every act of will, can see into the mind and know its hidden contents.\n\nAngels can know a person's thoughts indirectly, by observing their external effects: facial expressions, bodily movements, physiological changes. But the inner act of the will itself, in its secret and free dimension, is inaccessible to any creature. This is why only God is called the searcher of hearts."})

data.append({"index": "57.4b", "refashioned": "In this life, thoughts are hidden from others for two reasons: the opacity of the body and the concealment of the will. In the resurrection, bodily opacity will be removed, so the quality of a person's soul, its grace and glory, will be visible through the brightness of the body. But the will's free concealment remains, even for angels.\n\nOne angel can see the intelligible species in another angel's mind, since those species are natural endowments. But the actual use of those species, the free act of attending to this or thinking about that, is hidden until the angel chooses to reveal it."})

data.append({"index": "57.5a", "refashioned": "Angels do not know the mysteries of grace by their natural powers. Mysteries of grace depend on God's free will, and the free choices of God's will are known only to God unless he reveals them. Since supernatural mysteries (the Incarnation, the sacraments, the divine plan of salvation) flow from God's free decision, no angel can know them naturally.\n\nHowever, God does reveal mysteries of grace to angels. The mystery of the Incarnation, for example, was revealed to all angels from the beginning of their beatitude, since their ministry is ordered to it. Particular details and applications are revealed to different angels at different times according to God's plan."})

data.append({"index": "57.5b", "refashioned": "The Incarnation was revealed to all angels in general from the start, since their entire ministry is ordered to serving those who inherit salvation. But the particular details, timing, and circumstances were revealed progressively, as events unfolded. Higher angels know more of God's plan and communicate it to lower angels, who receive new insights as their missions require.\n\nThe essential point: angelic knowledge of grace is not natural but revealed. It is a gift, not an achievement of angelic intelligence."})

# =============================================================================
# Q58: Of the Mode of Angelic Knowledge
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "58.0", "refashioned": "Seven questions about how angels know: Is the angelic intellect sometimes potential, sometimes actual? Can an angel understand many things at once? Is angelic knowledge discursive? Do angels compose and divide concepts? Can there be falsehood in angelic intellect? Can angelic knowledge be called \"morning\" and \"evening\"? And are morning and evening knowledge the same?"})

data.append({"index": "58.1", "refashioned": "The angelic intellect is always in act with respect to its natural knowledge. Unlike the human intellect, which moves from potentiality to actuality as it learns, the angel possesses all its natural knowledge from the moment of creation. It does not need to acquire knowledge step by step.\n\nHowever, this does not mean the angel has no potentiality at all in its knowledge. With respect to supernatural knowledge, what God reveals over time, the angelic intellect can receive what it did not previously possess. And even with respect to natural knowledge, the angel may not always be actively considering everything it knows. It knows everything habitually but attends to particular objects by choice."})

data.append({"index": "58.2", "refashioned": "An angel can understand many things simultaneously, provided they are grasped through a single intelligible species. Since a single angelic species can represent many things (especially for higher angels, whose species are more universal), the angel can know all those things at once. But if multiple objects require multiple, distinct species, the angel must attend to them successively.\n\nThis differs from the human intellect, which can understand only one thing at a time through one species. The angel's greater intellectual power allows simultaneous knowledge of whatever falls under a single comprehensive form. The scope of simultaneous knowledge varies with the angel's rank: higher angels, with more universal species, can grasp more in a single act."})

data.append({"index": "58.3", "refashioned": "Angelic knowledge is not discursive. Discursive reasoning means moving from one known truth to another, as when we move from premises to conclusion in a syllogism. Angels do not reason this way. They see conclusions immediately in the principles, without needing to work through intermediate steps.\n\nThis is not because angels are incapable of grasping complex truths. It is because their intellect is powerful enough to see the whole logical structure at once. A human mind must build a chain of reasoning; an angelic mind sees the entire chain in a single glance. They know effects in their causes and conclusions in their principles simultaneously, not sequentially.\n\nAngels do know some things through other things. They know creatures through the divine ideas. But this is not discursive, because they see the cause and the effect together, not one after the other."})

data.append({"index": "58.4", "refashioned": "Angels do not understand by composing and dividing, that is, by forming judgments that combine subject and predicate the way we do. Human intellect first grasps simple concepts and then combines them into propositions. The angelic intellect grasps the complete truth about a thing in a single act, without needing to construct it from parts.\n\nHowever, angels can form propositions if they choose to. They are not incapable of compositional thought. They simply do not need it as a step toward understanding. They already see the whole truth that compositional thought would laboriously assemble."})

data.append({"index": "58.5", "refashioned": "There can be no falsehood in the angel's natural knowledge. With respect to what angels know naturally, through their innate species, they cannot err, because these species come directly from God and represent things as they truly are. Natural knowledge is infallible.\n\nHowever, angels can err in matters that exceed their natural knowledge. When they make judgments about future contingents, about the hidden thoughts of other minds, or about mysteries of grace, they can be mistaken. Demons, in particular, are subject to a kind of intellectual perversity: not that their natural knowledge is false, but that they misapply it, forming erroneous opinions about matters beyond their natural competence. Their error is not in seeing but in overreaching."})

data.append({"index": "58.7a", "refashioned": "Augustine distinguishes two kinds of angelic knowledge: \"morning knowledge\" and \"evening knowledge.\" Morning knowledge is knowledge of things as they exist in the Word of God, in God's eternal creative plan. Evening knowledge is knowledge of things as they exist in their own created natures.\n\nThese are two modes of knowing the same objects, not knowledge of two different sets of objects. The angel sees a creature in God's mind (morning knowledge) and also sees that same creature in its own created existence (evening knowledge). The distinction is one of perspective: from above, as God conceives it, or from below, as it exists in itself."})

data.append({"index": "58.7b", "refashioned": "Morning and evening knowledge are distinct but not unrelated. Augustine correlates them with the six days of creation: each \"day\" represents a class of things known by the angels first in God (morning) and then in themselves (evening). The angel always exercises morning knowledge, since it always sees things in God. But it also simultaneously or subsequently knows things in their own natures.\n\nThe key theological point: when evening knowledge is referred back to God's glory, it becomes the \"morning\" of the next day. That is, natural knowledge of creatures is perfected when it leads back to praise of the Creator. Knowledge of things in themselves is not bad, but it finds its completion in returning to God."})

# =============================================================================
# Q59: The Will of the Angels
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "59.0", "refashioned": "Four questions about angelic will: Do angels have a will? Is the will distinct from the intellect and nature? Do angels have free will? And do they have irascible and concupiscible appetites?"})

data.append({"index": "59.1", "refashioned": "Angels have a will. Will follows from intellect. Any being that understands the good necessarily has an appetite directed toward the good as such, and that rational appetite is will. Since angels are intellectual beings, they must have will.\n\nThe objection that will implies unfulfilled desire, and therefore imperfection, confuses will with wanting. Will in its fullest sense is not restless craving but the intellectual appetite's positive orientation toward the good. Even a being that possesses the good still wills it; the will rests in what it has. So the presence of will in angels is not a sign of deficiency but of intellectual nature operating at full capacity."})

data.append({"index": "59.2", "refashioned": "In angels, the will is really distinct from the intellect, just as the intellect is distinct from the angelic nature. The angel's nature is its essence. Its intellect is the power of knowing that flows from that essence. Its will is the power of desiring the good that flows from knowing it. These are distinct faculties with distinct acts: knowing and willing are not the same operation, even though they are inseparable in any intellectual being.\n\nThe natural inclination that comes from the angel's form (nature) is one thing. The inclination that follows from intellectual apprehension of the good (will) is another. Both are present in the angel, but they operate at different levels."})

data.append({"index": "59.3", "refashioned": "Angels have free will. Free will is the capacity to choose between alternatives in light of an intellectual judgment. Since angels have intellect and will, they can consider different goods and choose among them.\n\nThe objection that free will requires deliberation, and angels do not deliberate discursively, confuses the process with the capacity. Free will does not require step-by-step reasoning. It requires only that the agent be able to choose between goods that are not absolutely compelling. Since no created good is the infinite good, no created good compels an angelic will. The angel can always choose otherwise with respect to any finite good.\n\nWith respect to happiness in general, the will moves necessarily: every intellectual being necessarily wills to be happy. But with respect to particular goods that are not identical with happiness itself, the will is free."})

data.append({"index": "59.4a", "refashioned": "Angels do not have irascible and concupiscible appetites in the proper sense. These are sense appetites, powers tied to bodily organs. The irascible appetite responds to difficulty and threat; the concupiscible appetite responds to pleasure and attraction. Both involve physiological change, which angels, as incorporeal beings, cannot undergo.\n\nWhen Scripture attributes fury or desire to demons, it speaks metaphorically, describing the effects of their will in terms borrowed from human emotional experience. The demons do not literally feel rage or lust. Their will pursues certain goals with an intensity that resembles these passions, but without any bodily component."})

data.append({"index": "59.4b", "refashioned": "When love, joy, anger, or desire are attributed to angels or demons, these terms refer to acts of the intellectual will, not to bodily passions. Love in an angel is simply willing the good of another. Joy is the will resting in a good possessed. These are not emotions in the human sense. They involve no physiological arousal, no bodily disturbance. They are pure acts of an immaterial will.\n\nThe universal appetite of the will, which desires the good as such, encompasses everything that the irascible and concupiscible appetites pursue in embodied creatures, but it does so without the division into separate bodily powers."})

# =============================================================================
# Q60: Of the Love or Dilection of the Angels
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "60.0", "refashioned": "Five questions about angelic love: Is there natural love in angels? Is there elective love? Does an angel love itself naturally and by choice? Does it love other angels naturally as it loves itself? And does it love God more than itself by natural love?"})

data.append({"index": "60.1", "refashioned": "There is natural love in angels. Every being has a natural inclination toward what is good for it, and this inclination, in an intellectual being, is a form of love. The angel naturally loves its own existence, its own perfection, and the good that fulfills its nature. This natural love is not a choice; it is a built-in orientation of the will toward what is naturally fitting.\n\nThe objection that natural love is opposed to intellectual love confuses nature with mere instinct. In intellectual beings, the natural inclination of the will is itself intellectual. The angel's natural love is not a blind impulse but an intelligent orientation toward the good, grounded in its knowledge of its own nature."})

data.append({"index": "60.2", "refashioned": "Angels also have elective love, love that arises from free choice rather than natural inclination. Natural love is directed toward the end itself: the good as such. Elective love is directed toward means to the end, or toward particular goods that are not necessitated by nature.\n\nSince angels have free will, they can love things not merely because nature inclines them but because they freely judge something to be good and choose it. This is how angels can love supernatural goods, goods that exceed their natural orientation. It is also how fallen angels can love disordered goods, by freely choosing what does not accord with right order."})

data.append({"index": "60.3", "refashioned": "An angel loves itself with both natural love and elective love. By natural love, every being is inclined toward its own good and its own preservation. This is not selfishness; it is the basic orientation of any nature toward its own fulfillment. By elective love, the angel can also freely choose goods for itself, willing particular perfections and activities.\n\nThese two loves of self are not opposed. Natural self-love provides the foundation; elective self-love builds upon it by freely pursuing specific goods. A sinful angel's self-love becomes disordered not because self-love is inherently wrong, but because the angel chooses itself as its ultimate end rather than ordering itself toward God."})

data.append({"index": "60.4", "refashioned": "An angel naturally loves other angels as it loves itself, insofar as they share the same general nature. Just as every part of a whole naturally loves the whole and the other parts, so each angel, as a member of the angelic community and of the universe, naturally loves the other members. This natural love extends to all who share in intellectual nature, including human beings.\n\nThe depth of natural love corresponds to the degree of shared nature. An angel loves other angels more naturally than it loves material creatures, because the likeness is greater. But all natural love of others is ultimately rooted in the natural love of the common good, which encompasses everyone."})

data.append({"index": "60.5a", "refashioned": "By natural love, an angel loves God more than it loves itself. This is the most important claim in the whole discussion of angelic love. Every part naturally loves the whole more than itself. A hand naturally moves to protect the body even at cost to itself. Similarly, every creature naturally loves God, the universal good and source of all being, more than its own private good.\n\nThis is true even in the order of nature, apart from grace. The angel's natural orientation is toward God as the origin and end of all things. Self-love, properly ordered, is subordinate to love of God. The angel that loves itself rightly loves itself as something that exists for God's sake."})

data.append({"index": "60.5b", "refashioned": "The objection that things love what is closer over what is further does not apply here, because God is not just another being alongside the angel. God is the cause of the angel's very existence and goodness. When one thing is the total cause of another's being, the caused thing naturally loves the cause more than itself. The part loves the whole more than itself because the part depends entirely on the whole for its existence and meaning.\n\nThe objection that natural love is self-interested, that we love the good \"for ourselves,\" does not prove that the angel loves itself more than God. It proves only that the angel desires God as its good. But desiring God as your ultimate good means loving God more than yourself, not less, because your goodness depends entirely on God's."})

# =============================================================================
# Q61: Of the Production of the Angels in the Order of Natural Existence
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "61.0", "refashioned": "Having treated angelic nature, knowledge, and will, we now consider how angels were produced. Three topics: their natural existence, their perfection in grace and glory, and the fall of some into sin. On natural production, four questions: Do angels have a cause? Were they produced from eternity? Were they created before the material world? And were they created in the empyrean heaven?"})

data.append({"index": "61.1", "refashioned": "Angels have a cause of their existence: God created them. Although immaterial forms might seem to be self-sufficient (since they have no matter that needs a cause), every being whose essence is distinct from its existence requires a cause. Only God is his own existence. Every angel receives its existence from God, just as every other creature does.\n\nThe absence of explicit mention of angels in Genesis does not mean they were not created. Scripture's account of creation is adapted to the understanding of its original audience, and purely spiritual beings may be included implicitly or under symbolic language."})

data.append({"index": "61.2", "refashioned": "Angels were not produced from eternity. Only God is eternal. Even though God's creative power is eternal, its effect, the angel's existence, begins when God wills it to begin. An eternal cause can produce a temporal effect if the cause acts by free will rather than by natural necessity.\n\nAngels are above time in the sense that they are not measured by the continuous time of physical change. But they are not above every kind of temporal beginning. They began to exist at the first moment of creation, entering a mode of duration called aeviternity, which has a beginning but no end."})

data.append({"index": "61.3", "refashioned": "The question of whether angels were created before the corporeal world was debated. Some held that spiritual creation preceded material creation. Others held that both were created simultaneously.\n\nThe more defensible position is that angels were created at the same time as the material world. This fits the view that God created all things together in a single act. It also reflects the principle that parts of a whole are created together. Angels and material creatures are parts of one universe, and the universe, as a whole, was brought into being at once.\n\nHowever, this remains a question on which authoritative opinions differ, and no definitive doctrinal resolution has been reached."})

data.append({"index": "61.4", "refashioned": "Angels were created in the empyrean heaven, the highest corporeal place. Although angels do not depend on place for their existence, it was fitting that the noblest corporeal place should correspond to the noblest creatures. The empyrean heaven, understood as the place of divine glory, is where the angels first exercised their contemplation of God.\n\nThis does not mean angels are confined to the empyrean heaven. As spiritual beings, they can be present wherever they exercise their power. But their creation in the highest place symbolizes their role as the highest creatures, closest to God in the order of being."})

# =============================================================================
# Q62: Of the Perfection of the Angels in the Order of Grace and Glory
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "62.0", "refashioned": "Nine questions about angelic grace and glory: Were angels created in beatitude? Did they need grace to turn to God? Were they created in grace? Did they merit their beatitude? Did they achieve it immediately? Did they receive grace proportional to their natural gifts? Do natural knowledge and love remain after beatification? Can a beatified angel sin? And can beatified angels grow in blessedness?"})

data.append({"index": "62.1a", "refashioned": "Angels were not created in the full beatitude of seeing God. They were created in a state of natural perfection, with natural happiness, but not yet in the supernatural blessedness that comes from the direct vision of God's essence. That beatitude required a further step: the angel's free turning toward God, aided by grace.\n\nIf angels had been created already beatified, the fallen angels could never have fallen, since beatitude, once possessed, cannot be lost. Since some angels did fall, they had not yet attained final beatitude at the moment of creation."})

data.append({"index": "62.1b", "refashioned": "The \"beatitude\" attributed to angels at creation refers to their natural perfection, not to the supernatural vision of God. Just as corporeal creatures did not instantly achieve their full operational perfection but only the seeds of it, so the angels at creation possessed the perfection of their nature but not yet the perfection of glory. Natural perfection was the starting point; supernatural beatitude was the goal."})

data.append({"index": "62.2a", "refashioned": "Angels needed grace in order to turn to God in a way that merits supernatural beatitude. Natural love of God is real but insufficient. By nature, the angel loves God as the author of its natural being. But supernatural beatitude means seeing God's own essence, which surpasses any natural capacity. To orient itself toward this higher end, the angel needed a supernatural gift, grace, that elevated its will beyond its natural reach.\n\nThe fact that there was no obstacle in the angel's nature does not eliminate the need for grace. Grace is needed not because the task is difficult in the sense of requiring effort, but because it exceeds what any natural power can achieve. Flying is not difficult for a bird, but it is impossible for a stone, no matter how smooth the path."})

data.append({"index": "62.2b", "refashioned": "The angel loves God naturally insofar as God is the source of its natural being. But turning to God as the source of supernatural beatitude requires grace. \"Difficulty\" here does not mean resistance or struggle. It means exceeding the natural capacity. Without grace, the supernatural end is not merely hard but impossible, as impossible as flight for a creature without wings.\n\nGrace does not override the angel's natural love of God. It elevates it, redirecting the angel's already-existing love toward a higher object: God known not merely as cause but as he is in himself."})

data.append({"index": "62.3", "refashioned": "The most probable view is that angels were created in grace. They were not first created in a purely natural state and then later given grace. Rather, God gave them grace at the moment of creation, as a seed that would flower into glory if they freely cooperated.\n\nThis fits the general principle that God equips each creature from the start with what it needs for its proper perfection. Just as he gave nature its principles at creation, so he gave the angels grace at creation. The angels did not earn this initial grace; it was a gift accompanying their nature."})

data.append({"index": "62.4", "refashioned": "Angels merited their beatitude. Although they received grace freely, they had to use it freely to merit the reward of glory. Merit requires a free act directed toward the end, aided by grace. The angels who remained faithful freely cooperated with grace and thereby earned their eternal blessedness.\n\nThe objection that angels faced no difficulty, and therefore no merit, misunderstands merit. Merit does not require suffering or struggle. It requires a free act of the will, empowered by grace, directed toward an end that exceeds natural capacity. The angel's free choice to love God above all, made in the first moment of its moral life, was genuinely meritorious."})

data.append({"index": "62.5", "refashioned": "Angels obtained beatitude immediately after one act of merit. They did not need a long process of repeated meritorious acts the way humans do. The reason is that angels do not learn gradually or reason discursively. In a single act, the angel grasped and chose its ultimate end with the full force of its intellect and will. One complete act was sufficient.\n\nThis makes sense given the angelic mode of operation. Humans need time because our knowledge and willing develop incrementally. Angels operate with an intensity and comprehensiveness that allows a single act to accomplish what we achieve over a lifetime. The angel's first free act was also its definitive act."})

data.append({"index": "62.6", "refashioned": "Angels received grace and glory in proportion to their natural gifts. The more perfect the angel's nature, the more grace it received, and the greater its resulting glory. This is not because nature earns grace, but because God, in his wisdom, proportions his supernatural gifts to the natural capacity of the recipient. A larger vessel receives more, not because the vessel deserves it, but because the giver wisely fills each according to its capacity.\n\nThis means the hierarchy of glory among the angels mirrors the hierarchy of nature. The highest angels by nature are also the highest in grace and glory. Natural perfection, grace, and glory form a single ascending order, all flowing from God's unified creative and sanctifying plan."})

data.append({"index": "62.7", "refashioned": "Natural knowledge and love remain in the beatified angels. Glory does not destroy nature but perfects it. The angel's natural knowledge of itself, of other angels, and of God as cause continues in the state of beatitude. Supernatural knowledge (seeing God's essence) is added on top of natural knowledge, not substituted for it.\n\nSimilarly, natural love, the angel's innate orientation toward its own good and toward God as its source, persists alongside the supernatural love of charity. The two are not in competition. Natural love is taken up into and elevated by supernatural love, like a candle flame that continues to burn even when the sun rises."})

data.append({"index": "62.8", "refashioned": "A beatified angel cannot sin. Once an angel has attained the direct vision of God, its will is permanently fixed on God as the supreme good. Seeing God as he truly is removes every possibility of choosing something else as an ultimate end. There is no alternative that could appear more attractive, because the angel sees the infinite good itself.\n\nFree will remains, but it operates within the orientation established by the vision of God. The angel is free in the sense that it can choose among various goods. But it cannot choose against God, because no finite good, seen in the light of the infinite good, could ever appear worth preferring. This is not a limitation of freedom but its perfection: freedom fully directed by the truth."})

data.append({"index": "62.9a", "refashioned": "Beatified angels do not advance in beatitude. Their blessedness is final and complete. Merit belongs to the state of moving toward an end, not to the state of having arrived. Once the angel possesses God in the beatific vision, there is no further end to move toward, and therefore no further merit to earn.\n\nThis does not mean the angel's blessedness is static in the sense of being boring or empty. It means the angel possesses the fullness of what it was created for. There is no lack to be remedied, no further degree of perfection to be attained. The angel rests in God as its complete and final good."})

data.append({"index": "62.9b", "refashioned": "Merit belongs to those who are still on the way to their end. A being that has already arrived at its ultimate end does not merit but simply possesses. The beatified angel has reached its final state and rests there. Its acts of service, such as ministering to human beings, proceed from its already-complete blessedness and are not ways of earning additional reward. The angel's charity in glory is perfect charity, and perfect charity is not a means to an end but the end itself, fully realized."})

# =============================================================================
# Q63: The Malice of the Angels with Regard to Sin
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "63.0", "refashioned": "Nine questions about how angels became evil: Can angels sin? What kinds of sin are possible for them? What did the devil seek in sinning? Are any demons naturally evil? Was the devil evil from the first instant of his creation? Was there an interval between creation and the fall? Was the highest-ranking sinner the highest of all angels? Did his sin cause the others to sin? And did as many angels sin as remained faithful?"})

data.append({"index": "63.1a", "refashioned": "Angels can sin. Although their nature is purely intellectual and their natural knowledge is infallible, they have free will, and free will carries the possibility of choosing wrongly. The evil possible in angels is not a corruption of their nature (which remains intact even in demons) but a disorder of their free choice.\n\nThe key distinction is between natural operation and free operation. Natural angelic operations cannot go wrong, just as the motions of heavenly bodies cannot err. But free operations, which go beyond what nature determines, can deviate from right order. Sin in angels is the misuse of freedom, not the corruption of nature."})

data.append({"index": "63.1b", "refashioned": "There is no potentiality in angels for natural deficiency, but there is potentiality in their will for disordered choice. That is where evil can enter. Their natural knowledge is infallible, their natural tendencies are good, but their free will can orient itself wrongly. Even a perfect intellect with perfect natural knowledge can choose to prefer its own good over the universal good, and that is precisely what the fallen angels did."})

data.append({"index": "63.2", "refashioned": "Only sins of pride and envy can exist in angels. Sins that involve bodily pleasure, sensory desire, or material attachment are impossible for incorporeal beings. Angels have no bodies and therefore no capacity for lust, gluttony, or sloth in the physical sense.\n\nPride and envy are spiritual sins. Pride is the disordered desire for one's own excellence. Envy is sorrow at another's good, insofar as it diminishes one's own relative standing. These do not require a body. They require only a will that can orient itself toward its own private good in defiance of the universal order.\n\nWhen demons are said to delight in carnal sins, this is not because they experience physical pleasure. They delight in the disorder, in the human degradation and the rebellion against God that such sins represent."})

data.append({"index": "63.3a", "refashioned": "Did the devil desire to be God? This requires careful analysis. There are two ways to desire equality with God: literally, by wanting to be identical with God, and by likeness, by wanting to be like God in some specific way."})

data.append({"index": "63.3b", "refashioned": "The devil sinned by desiring to be like God, not by desiring literal equality with God. The angel knew, by natural knowledge, that becoming God was impossible. No creature can become infinite, and any angel understood this. Furthermore, even if it were possible, no creature would naturally desire it, because becoming a different nature means ceasing to be what you are. An ass does not desire to be a horse, because if it became one, it would no longer exist.\n\nSo the devil's sin was subtler. He desired likeness to God in a specific way: he wanted to achieve his final happiness through his own power rather than through God's grace. He wanted to be the source of his own blessedness, to be self-sufficient in the way only God is self-sufficient. He wanted the goal (likeness to God) by the wrong means (his own power rather than God's gift).\n\nAlternatively, he desired to have dominion and excellence beyond what God's order assigned him, wanting to rule others as God rules, by his own authority rather than under God's. Either way, the sin was not wanting something impossible but wanting something by a means that was not his to claim. He sought to be an end unto himself, which is God's prerogative alone."})

data.append({"index": "63.4", "refashioned": "No demon is naturally evil. Every nature, as created by God, is good. Evil in angels comes entirely from the misuse of free will, not from any defect in their created nature. The demonic nature remains as good as the angelic nature it was created to be. What is corrupted is the will, not the substance.\n\nThe claim that demons are \"naturally\" crafty or deceitful confuses nature with habit. Their deceptiveness is a consequence of their sinful orientation, not a feature of their original design. God does not create evil natures. He creates good natures that freely chose evil."})

data.append({"index": "63.5a", "refashioned": "Was the devil evil from the very first instant of his creation? Some say yes: that the instant he was made, he sinned. Others say there was at least a brief interval in which he was good before he fell."})

data.append({"index": "63.5b", "refashioned": "The devil was not evil in the first instant of his creation. He was created good, with a good nature and in a state of grace. His sin came afterward, though without any measurable delay in our time.\n\nThe reasoning: the angel's first act must have been a natural act, and natural acts in angels are always good. The angel's nature inclines it toward the good. Its first movement, arising from its nature before any free choice intervenes, was necessarily good. Sin required a second act, a free choice that departed from the natural orientation toward God.\n\nScripture supports this: \"You were perfect in your ways from the day of your creation, until iniquity was found in you.\" The devil was created perfect and then fell. His fall was not instantaneous with his creation but followed it, however closely."})

data.append({"index": "63.5c", "refashioned": "When Scripture says the devil \"sins from the beginning,\" it means from the beginning of his sin, not from the beginning of his existence. He never repented, so his sin has been continuous from the moment it began. But that moment was not the moment of his creation.\n\nThe distinction between light and darkness in the creation narrative, as Augustine reads it, refers to God's foreknowledge of which angels would stand and which would fall, not to their being created in two different moral states."})

data.append({"index": "63.6", "refashioned": "There was no extended interval between the angel's creation and his fall. The angel's intellectual and volitional operations are not measured by continuous time the way ours are. The angel was created, performed one good act (its natural first act), and then in the very next instant of its deliberation, fell.\n\nThe idea that the angel \"walked in perfection\" for a long time before falling reads too much into the metaphor. Angelic time is not our time. What might be described as a sequence from one perspective happened with a swiftness that defies temporal measurement. Creation, the first good act, and then the fall, all in rapid succession, with no prolonged period of innocence between."})

data.append({"index": "63.7", "refashioned": "The highest angel among those who sinned was indeed the highest of all the angels. His sin was pride, and pride is proportional to excellence. The most gifted angel had the most to be proud of, and his pride was accordingly the greatest. Scripture's references to the fallen angel as the \"anointed cherub\" and the bearer of the \"seal of resemblance\" suggest a being of supreme natural endowment.\n\nThis does not mean that being the highest angel caused the fall. It means that the occasion for pride was greatest in the most excellent being. The highest angel had the most reason to be satisfied with his own power and the strongest temptation to seek self-sufficiency rather than dependence on God."})

data.append({"index": "63.8", "refashioned": "The sin of the highest angel was the cause of the other angels' sin, not by compulsion but by persuasion and influence. The other fallen angels chose to follow his lead freely. They sinned through the same kind of pride, desiring to be subject to the highest angel in imitation of his self-exaltation rather than remaining subject to God.\n\nThis parallels how sin works among humans: one person's bad example and influence leads others into similar choices, without removing their responsibility. The leader's sin did not necessitate the followers' sin. Each fallen angel chose independently, but the leader's rebellion provided the occasion and the model."})

data.append({"index": "63.9", "refashioned": "More angels remained faithful than fell. Sin is contrary to the natural inclination of intellectual beings, which is toward the good. Since angels have perfect natural knowledge and a strong natural orientation toward God, the majority followed that orientation. The fallen angels are the exception, not the rule.\n\nScripture supports this indirectly. When it speaks of angelic hosts and their vast numbers, the implication is that the heavenly armies far outnumber the fallen. Evil, being a privation and a departure from nature, is always in the minority when measured against the created order's fundamental orientation toward the good."})

# =============================================================================
# Q64: The Punishment of the Demons
# =============================================================================

data.append({"index": "64.0", "refashioned": "Four questions about the punishment of demons: Is their intellect darkened? Is their will fixed in evil? Do they experience sorrow? And is our atmosphere their place of punishment?"})

data.append({"index": "64.1a", "refashioned": "Are demons deprived of all knowledge of truth? If they retained any knowledge, would that not be a kind of happiness? But total ignorance seems inconsistent with their nature as intellectual beings."})

data.append({"index": "64.1b", "refashioned": "Demons retain their natural knowledge but lose the knowledge that comes from grace. There are three kinds of knowledge of truth: natural (flowing from the angel's nature as an intellect), gratuitous speculative (divine secrets revealed by grace), and the affective wisdom that produces love of God. The first remains in demons. The second is diminished but not entirely removed, since God still reveals certain things to demons through angels. The third is entirely lost.\n\nNatural knowledge remains because it belongs to the angel's nature, which is not destroyed by sin. The angel's intellectual substance is intact. What is lost is the supernatural light and the loving orientation toward divine truth. Demons can still know truths, but they cannot love the truth they know, and they are cut off from the intimate knowledge of God that beatified angels enjoy."})

data.append({"index": "64.1c", "refashioned": "Knowing other spiritual substances is natural for angels and does not constitute happiness. Human happiness might consist in knowing separated substances because such knowledge exceeds our natural capacity. But for an angel, knowing other angels is routine, like our knowledge of everyday objects. Demonic knowledge of natural truths, however extensive, does not give them joy, because they cannot refer that knowledge to God or take delight in the order of creation. Their knowledge is accurate but loveless, and loveless knowledge of the good is itself a form of torment."})

data.append({"index": "64.2a", "refashioned": "Is the demons' will permanently fixed in evil? Free will seems to imply the ability to change. And God's infinite mercy seems capable of restoring any sinner. So why cannot demons repent?"})

data.append({"index": "64.2b", "refashioned": "The demons' will is irrevocably fixed in evil. This is not because God withholds mercy from willing penitents, but because demons are constitutionally incapable of repentance. Here is why.\n\nAngelic choice is total and definitive in a way human choice is not. Humans deliberate step by step, change their minds, learn from consequences, and can reverse course. Angels grasp everything relevant to a choice in a single comprehensive act. When an angel chooses, it does so with full intellectual clarity and total volitional commitment. There is nothing left to learn that might change its mind. Its choice exhausts the deliberative process in one act.\n\nThis means that the angel's first free choice, for or against God, is permanent. The good angels are permanently fixed in good, and the fallen angels are permanently fixed in evil. Neither can reverse course, because there is no new information or perspective that could prompt a reconsideration. The choice was made with the full resources of an angelic intellect, and nothing can undo it."})

data.append({"index": "64.2c", "refashioned": "Both good and fallen angels have free will, but in different states. The good angels' free will is permanently directed toward God. The fallen angels' free will is permanently turned from God. Both are free in the sense that their choices were voluntary. Neither is free to reverse course, because angelic choice, once made with full clarity, is by nature irrevocable.\n\nGod's mercy extends to those who repent. Demons cannot repent, not because mercy is withheld but because repentance is impossible for a being that chose with total clarity and finality. The devil's original desire remains in force, not because he still thinks he can achieve it, but because his will is set in the posture of that first refusal and cannot reorient itself."})

data.append({"index": "64.3", "refashioned": "Demons experience sorrow. They know that their suffering is just, they see the good they have lost, and they are tormented by the success of those they envy. Their will is set on evil, but they do not achieve everything they will. Every thwarting of their desire is a source of grief. They rejoice in the evil they accomplish and grieve over the evil they are prevented from accomplishing.\n\nThis coexistence of joy and sorrow is not contradictory. They are directed at different objects. The demon takes a perverse satisfaction in the harm it causes but suffers genuine anguish at its own punishment, at the triumph of the good, and at the gap between what it desires and what it obtains. Their existence is a mixture of malicious glee and inescapable torment."})

data.append({"index": "64.4", "refashioned": "The demons' place of punishment is twofold: hell and the lower atmosphere of the earth. Hell is their primary place of punishment. But some demons are permitted to inhabit the air around the earth until the final judgment, as a trial for human beings. They operate in our world not because they are free but because God permits their presence as a test.\n\nThis arrangement is not inconsistent with their punishment. A prisoner can be taken from his cell to labor without ceasing to be punished. The demons carry their punishment with them wherever they go. Their torment is not primarily a matter of location but of the permanent condition of their will, which is turned from God and fixed in misery. They are in hell wherever they are, because hell, for a spiritual being, is ultimately a state of the will rather than a geographical coordinate.\n\nAt the final judgment, all demons will be confined to hell permanently. Their current presence in our atmosphere is temporary, permitted by God for the testing and spiritual growth of the human race."})

